Equal to the Loci 4 and 6 Fill/Debris that overlies it. Seals Fill/Locus 16. Built up to the northeast face of the Orchestra Retaining Wall Locus 12, the south face of the Pulpitum Wall Locus 14, and the west face of the central Platform Locus 19. Equal to Loci 4 and 6 Fill/Debris.
Measurements: 7.0 m in length (north-south), 3.90 m in width (east-west), 1.10 m (north) and 1.31 m (south) in depth.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of major temple architectural elements including the West Porch columns. Collapse and accumulation of debris around the temple east columns and on top of the lower risers of interior and rear staircases. Buckling of the west intercolumnar wall. Possible conflagration. Primary fluvial layer is deposited.
Phase XI: Further collapse post CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. The east Porch columns and Central Arch collapse and fluvial deposits continue to accumulate.
Top elevation: 906.806 m at the north, 906.836 m at the center, 906.736 at the south.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c, Upper level robbing occurs including the upper treads of East and West Interior and Rear Staircases, and the associated upper landings. Evidence of squatter camps in the South Corridor and Central Arch.

Lowest level of fill/debris from the collapse of the Temple structure filling the Orchestra from the top of the Retaining Wall Locus 12 down to just above the floor level sealing Fill Locus 16. This locus consists of large stone architectural debris with sandy fill. Most of the architectural fragments found were sculpted pieces from the capitals that fell into the Theater area from the West Colonnade. In addition there was a column drum (along with numerous fragments of white fluted plaster from the collapsed columns), moldings, several vault stones and one fragment of a marble tile. Green painted wall plaster found in the fill and on the face of several stones (including two L-shaped stones) gives an indication of the color scheme of the Theater area although it is unclear from where this green plaster originated.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Major collapse of the temple structure and the accumulation of architectural debris over the orchestra floor and the lower Theater seats.
